The two following odes treat a single theme—the immortality of song.

‘Bronzes, marbles, pictures l have none to give, good friend Censo- rinus, nor wouldst thou desire thern. Song is thy delight, and song l can bestow. The chiseled record of men's deeds is weaker than the lluse. Through her gift the great ones of the past escaped oblivion. and have their place in heaven'

C. Marcius Censorinus, cos. 8 B.c., is known only from these verses and a single reference in Velleius. It has been conjectured not without reason that this ode was Horace's gift to his friend on the Calends of March or on the Saturnalia, when presents were exchanged as at our Christmas. Metre, 53.
